---
description: File structure per component — styles, types, utils, tests, and index separated
globs: "**/*.tsx"
alwaysApply: true
---

# Component File Structure

Every component MUST have its own folder with separated files. No exceptions.

## Required Files

```
ComponentName/
  ComponentName.tsx          → Component implementation
  ComponentName.types.ts     → Props interface and local types
  ComponentName.test.tsx     → Unit tests (TDD — see testing-tdd rule)
  index.ts                   → Named re-export only (ALWAYS exists)
```

## Optional Files

```
  ComponentName.module.scss  → Styles (create ONLY when the component has its own styles)
  ComponentName.utils.ts     → Helper functions (create ONLY when needed)
```

Wrapper/provider components (e.g., `AppProviders`, `AuthGuard`) that compose other components without adding visual styles do NOT need `.module.scss`. Sub-components within a module may import the parent's `.module.scss` instead of creating their own. NEVER create empty files — if the component has no styles, omit the file.

## File Responsibilities

### `ComponentName.types.ts`
```typescript
import type { UserResponse } from '@/services/user'

export interface UserCardProps {
  variant: 'default' | 'compact'
  user: UserResponse
  onSelect: (user: UserResponse) => void
}
```

### `ComponentName.tsx`
```tsx
import clsx from 'clsx'
import { Text } from '@primer/react'
import { useTranslation } from 'react-i18next'
import type { UserCardProps } from './UserCard.types'
import styles from './UserCard.module.scss'

export const UserCard = ({ variant, user, onSelect }: UserCardProps) => {
  const { t: tCommon } = useTranslation('common')

  return (
    <div className={clsx(styles.root, styles[variant])} onClick={() => onSelect(user)}>
      <Text as="p">{user.name}</Text>
      <Text as="span">{tCommon('actions.edit')}</Text>
    </div>
  )
}
```

### `ComponentName.utils.ts`
```typescript
export const formatUserDisplayName = (name: string, email: string) =>
  `${name} (${email})`
```

### `index.ts`
```typescript
export { UserCard } from './UserCard'
export type { UserCardProps } from './UserCard.types'
```

## Rules

- NEVER put types inline in the component file
- NEVER export default — always named exports
- NEVER accept `className`, `style`, or styling props — use `variant` only (see styling-conventions rule)
- `.utils.ts` is OPTIONAL — create ONLY when the component has helper functions. NEVER create empty files
- `.module.scss` is OPTIONAL — create ONLY when the component has its own styles. Wrappers/providers may omit it
- When styles exist, they MUST live in `.module.scss` — never inline in `.tsx`
- `index.ts` is the ONLY entry point — ALWAYS exists, never import from internal files outside the folder
- Props types import from `services/` types when representing domain data
- Visible strings use `useTranslation` — never hardcoded (see i18n rule)

## Exception — Icons Atom

The `Icons` atom groups multiple SVG icon components in a single folder. It does NOT follow the one-component-per-folder convention:

```
atoms/Icons/
  GoogleIcon.tsx       → One file per icon (no .module.scss needed)
  Icons.types.ts       → Shared IconProps type
  Icons.test.tsx       → Tests for all icons
  index.ts             → Named re-exports
```

Icons are pure SVG components that receive `SVGProps<SVGSVGElement>`. They have no styles, no state, and no translations. ALL custom SVG icons MUST live here — NEVER in app modules or utils.

## Exceptions to Named Exports

`export default` is allowed ONLY when a third-party library requires it:

- `i18next` configuration (`export default i18n`)
- Ambient type declarations (`*.d.ts` files)

These exceptions NEVER apply to component, module, service, or hook files.
